{"/service/ndnp/scu/batch_scu_dogwood_ver01/data/sn84026925/0029586283A/1921021801/0112.xml":{"full_text":"Itumorous department.\nWell Preserved.?Former Senator\nJohn Weeks, of Massachusetts, has\nlong enjoyed an established reputation\nas a naval expert; but only lately\nhas he blossomed out as an Orientalist.\nA few days ago at a public\ngathering he made formal announce^\nInent of a highly important discovery\nof a collection of Babylonian tablets\ncovered with coneiform inscriptions.\nMr. Weeks said that the importance'\nof these tablets was entirely due to\nihoiv snhiert matter. As a rule.\nChaldean tablets bear records of laws,\ncommercial transactions and royal decrees;\nbut those to which the speaker\nreferred preserved for a remote posterity\nspecimens of eastmen humor\nthat were hoary with ape when Babylon\nwas a village.\nOne ct these tablets, according to\nMr. Weeks, chronicled a royal ball\nthat the king gave in honor of one of\nMethuselah's birthdays, when that\nnotoriously aged person was .pretty\nwell along in years. It appeared that\none of the ladies of the court, having\npaid her respects to the guest of honor,\nmade bold to ask him which birthday\nhe was celebrating.\n\"I am nine hundred and sixty years\nold to-day, my dear,\" replied the ancient.\n\"You don't say so!\" replied the lady\nin her best society manner. \"You don't\nlook a day over nine hundred and\nthirty.\"'\nDccpV Moved.?Jn tho recent campaign\nA statesman from below Mason\napd Dixon's line, distinguished for\nhis oratorical gifts, was persuaded to\nassist a fellow Democrat in a northern\nstate, seeking reelection.\nThe silver-tongued southerner therefore\nhad occasion to address a meeting\nin a small but politically enthusiastic\ncommunity.\nHe made a very eloquent appeal for\nsupport for his colleague, at the conelusion\nof which a very local orchestra,\nengaged for the purpose, undertook\nto pay a musical tribute to the\nvisiting speaker by rendering My Old\nKentucky Home.\nThe instrumentalists were more energetic\nthan musical, yet the old air\nwas recognizable and tho speaker was\nmuch impressed, more perhaps with\ntho spirit of the orchestral effort than\nits success.\nAs he looked over the audience he\nobserved a man seated near the\norchestra, apparently intent upon the\nmusic. The man was visibly overcome.\nTears streamed down his\ncheeks.\nI ne souinern ?ui,iesuiuii wumru\nover to the man and said: \"I sympathize\nwith you, suh, residing1, as you\n<lu, so far from your homeland. What\npart of the south are you from7\"\n\"Hell,\" replied the other, \"I'm no\nsoutherner. 1'irt a musician.\"\nHogg Versus Hogg.?Former Senator\nJohn W. Weeks, of Massachusetts,\nwas lately recalling to a party of\nfriends scjme of the happy days of the\nlong ago in Washington.\nIn those days, he said, there were\nsuch things as bars; and lus old\nfriend Hirtubiis Hog spent a great\ndeal of his time on the fringe of these\noases.\nOne night, after an .unusually long\nsojourn near his favorite bar, Mr. Hogg\nnavigated painfully home and at last\nfound himself safe and sound in his\nbedroom. Mrs. Hogg was waiting up\nfor him.\n\"Hirtubus,\" she said, after a\" swift\nnnnr.n insil nf his Condition. \"I am\nashamed of you?utterly ashamed.\nYou are a Hogg hy name and a hog\nby nature.\"\n\"Yes. nt'dear,\" .replied the prodigal\nmeekly, \"but even at that I have the\nadvantage over you.\n\"You are a Hogg by name, but you.\nbecame a: Hogg by choice.\"\nHis Knowledge Limited.?Samuel\nHopkins Adains tells ol' a friend up in\nhis part of the country who purchased\na flivver and without any knowledge\nof that kind cf car decided to drive\nit home.\nTwo miles out of town the little\nfdvver gave a spasmodic gasp and\ndied in the middle of the road. He\ntried cranKltlj, tnrowing sunn in ?ue\nrqdiator and finally kicked it in the\ntomaeli. All to no avail. The engine\nsimply would not start. Finally he\nspied a big ten-thousand-dollar car\ncoming down the road, lfe held up\nhis hand for it to slop.\nThe big machine slowed down and\ncame to a graceful stop alongside the\nstricken flivver.\n\"Say.\" called out Mr. Adams' friend\nto the chauffeur, \"do you know any>\nthing about a flivver?\"\n\"Nothing,\"-he repHed, \"but a couple\nof funny stories.\"\n?o?\nThought Her Mrs. Ty.?At a theater\nin Savannah, Georgia, some tickets\nhad been left for Mrs. Irvin S. Cobb,\nwho was visiting relatives. The young\nman at the window was unusually attentive\nand cordial when Mrs. Cobb\ncalled.\n\"If there is anything in the world we\nran do for you, Mrs. Cobb, let us\nKnow,\" lie said. \"\\ve are an -great\nadmirers of your husband.\"\n\"That Is awfully nice of you,\" she\nreplied, thanking him.\n\"i see he hit well over .300. even if\nlie didn't cop the big honor,\" the^ young\nman remarked. Do you know. Mrs.\nColili, if he gets off well in the spring\nhe'll lead the league again sure. That\nhoy certainly swings a mean bat!\"\nTake Your Choice.?\"My dear,\" said\nMrs. IVrriva! I'inoehle.\n\"Yes. lovely,\" said I'ere.\n\"Shall we drive over and get five\ngallons of gasoline or will you walk to\ntown and buy a four-pound roast?\"\neditors of leading newspapers. aim\nuniversity economists, announced in\nthe February til issue of the Literary\nDigest.\nProminent in the published opinions\non the return of prosperity are quotations\nfrom Chicago men, including J.\nOgden Armour, president of Armour\nCo.: E. A. Cudaliy, Jr., vice president\nof the Cmlahy Packing company:\nV. D. Shipworth, vice president of Wilson\nCo.: Albert Pick, president of\nAlbert Pick Co..and others including\nKdwin Nichols, financial editor\nof The Daily News and Prof. II. A.\nMills, II. tJ. Moulton and Chester W.\n1 Wright, of the political economy and\neconomics departments of the t'niverI\nsity of Chicago.\nPatterson Tells Reasons.\n\"The world's business is in trouble,\"\nI \\yijtcs John II. Patterson, president, of\nthe National\"Cash- Register eompahy!\"\nin one of the leading com month iTes.\"Soiuo\nnations cannot sell their surplus\nof agriculture, industries and\neral montns ago iu umc me\ned second assistant District Attorney.\n.Mr. W.vche will continue to handle\nthe business of his office until March\n1st, when he will move into the office\nnow occupied by the firm of which lie\nis to become a partner. He will probably\nassist in all cases to be handled\nby the firm at the next term of court,\nincluding the defense of Tom Hanison.\nfor the alleged killing of his wife.\n?(ireonville Piedmont.\nPROSPERITY ON WAY\nSlow But Steady Improvement Shown\nby Poll.\n\"The worst is over; conditions will\nimprove steadily hut slowly.\" This is\nthe mass opinion on the return of!\nprosperity as found by a nation-wide\npoll of big business men, financial\nWYCHE TO QUIT\nWestern District Assistant Attorney\nWill Enter Private Practice.\nC. (J. Wyche, who for several years\nhas been assistant United States District\nattorney for the western district\nof South Carolina, announced today\nl hat his resignation, as assistant District\nAttorney, to take effect at. the\nclose' of business February 2Sth, went\nto Washington today.\nMr. Wyche recently became associated\nwith A. II. Dean and W. C.\nCoihrnn, forming the firm of Dean.\nC'othran and Wyche, for practice here.\nThe firm was more recently known\nas Cotliran, Dean nnd Coihrnn, but\nwith the elevation of the senior partner,\nThos. P. Cothran to the supreme\nbench of South Carolina, it was re-organized,\nwith Mr. Wyche as a partner.\"\nSucceeding Mr. Wyche as assistant\nDistrict Attorney, is John E. Marshal\nwho came here from Cr'eenwood sev\nsources that they have tiled like flies J\non the way.\n\"There is no question that more\nthan 10,000,000 Chinese will, starve to\ndeath this winter and spring un'ess\nfood is rushed to them.\" He declared\nthat millions will die despite aid,\nthat the population of 45.000.000 in\nthe famine districts is in such /lire\nstraits that it will le a physical impossibility\nto rush enough food to\nthem to save all.\nGreat irrigation projects, control of\nflood producing streams, and improvement\nof transportation were cited'byMr.\nGlines as the\" only salvation of\nthe agricultural and economic life of\nChina.\n'These things will be done in time\"\nhe said, \"for China is awake, America\nwill probably hove a bjg part in this\nfuture of China, but we must lay\naside these things for the present and\ndevote every effort to getting food to\nthe starving millions.\"\nlargely an agricultural nation. Ninety\nper cent, of the population lives on\nthe liny farms into which the country\nis divided. The Chinese- work their\nland to the limit but they cannot\nraise more than enough to feed themselves.\nEach district can raise barely\nenough food, to support its own people.\nTha.t is why the 'prosperous'\nprovinces have been able to do so little\nfor the famine stricken ones. They\nhave not the food 'to send.\n\"The crops in North China have\nfailed since 1919. The people have\nbeen unable to get more than scraps\nof food from other parts of China.\nThey have been unable to get much\nfrom outside because food has been\nhigh priced all over the world.\" They\nhave tried to move to better districts\nwhere they have had such poor re- j\nWAITED JN VAIN\nChinese Starved to Death Believing\nFood Was Coming.\nThirty thousand Chinese gathered\nin a'great bare field outside Tientsin.\nChina, waiting patiently for food\nwhich never arrived and then slowly\ndied there, B. S. Glines, American en'p'lneor,\nreported ,.upori his nrrivul in\nNew York after passing six months\nitf'the farpine .stricken areas of North\nChina, relates an Associated Press\ndispatch.. i lft;u.\nThe condition of the starving'hordes\nc%%\\ i'llinac coifl thflt lie\nVY il?> OVi [JAW. Ul,, UT&,* Vaiiivu --\"did\nnot. have, the heart to tuke photographs\nof such misery.\"' *He said\nthat the crowd at Tientsin had gathered\nbecause they believed food would,\nreach them there more quickly than in\nthe country. Ajong a roadside near\nthe field, he told of seeing the bodies\nof a whole family?father, mother and\nfive children?each a few yards apart\nwhere they had dropped and died.\n\"The crop failures have been almost\ncomplete in the five great provinces\nthat make up the northern\npart of China proper?Chihli, Shantung,\nShansi, Shensi and Honan,\"\nsaid Mr. Glines. \"This is the part of\nthe country around Peking, south of\nMongolia and Manchuria.\"\nExplaining why the sections of\nChina not stricken by famine were\nunable to relieve, the starvation districts.\nMr. Glines said: \"China is\nminerals. Other nations greatly need\nthem. Plenty of idle ships to carry\nthem. Millions of people out of employment.\"\nPRANK OF THE WIND.\nHundreds of Snowballs Were Rolled\nUp On New York Farm\nWhen Pete Finigin went out to do\nthe chores one morning recently he\nwas mysuneu oy me sigm vi u. icugo\nnumber n of huge snowballs scattered\nover his farm, relates an Avon, N. -Y.,\ndispatch. On the 20-acre field there\nwere hundreds of them ranging in size\nfront G to IS inches in diameter. Leading\nup to each snovi'bal! was a streak\nof bare ground showing the distance\nit had traveled in forming.\nMr. Fin i gin and neighbors who\ngathered' to study the odd spectacle\ndecided that the wind which had blown\nai gale the night gefore had whipped\nup small particles of \"good packing\"\nsnow and started them down the field,\nsome of the particle's gathering up additional\nsnow until balls had been\nformed that were too heavy for the\nwind to move further. All the paths\nof'the snowballs were in the same\ngeneral direction .that the wind had\nbeen blowing.\nTo record the unusual freak of wind\nand snow, Mr. Finigin sent for the\ncorrespondent of a l'ualffo newspaper,\nw'ho counted more than 1,000 snowballs\nof more than 10 Inches in diameter.\nDEMPSEY IS BUSY\nAmerican Boxing Champion Going On\nTour of Europe.\nJack Dempsey, world's heavyweight\nchampion will make a European tour\nnext month, says a New York dispatch.\nHe wl'l go to England and\nFrance for exhibition bouts that will\nexlend over six weeks. Present plans\nprovide only for his meeting sparring\npartners who will accompany him, as\nhe can take part in no contest before\nhis bout with Carpentier which has\nbeen set for July '1 at New York.\nJack Kearns, Dempsey'3 manager,\nmade this announcement during a\n\\-ic-it Vi?i-n Tin H hr? vvns in\ntouch with European promoters and\ndates for Hie champion's nppearanee\nwere assured.\nDempsey himself wired him from\nSalt Lake City today, ho said, that\nhe was ro.i'lv w> start training at once\nwith the idea of sailing in two weeks.\nKcarns said the sailing would be from\nNew York about March 1.\nKearns said he was returning to\nNew York tomorrow to clear up questions\nregarding the forfeits and arrangements\nfor the .Carpentier bout!\nMeantime ho was looking over the\nfield here with a view to arranging\nfor a bout here next slimmer between\nDempsey and Jess Wlllinrd or Frank\nMoran.\n\n1^1\nDETECTIVE DOGS\nGerman Police Said to be Without a\nPeer.\n\"Latest style in dogs\" is the title\ngiven the German police dogs by Dean\nvv. Horace HosKins or tne i\\?\\v ioi-k\nUniversity Veterinary college who says\nfashions in dogs fluctuate as they (3o\nin dress.\nThe IJoston terrier and Pehlnese are\nalso fashionable Dean Hoskini said.\n\"The Boston terrier has enjoyed a\nlonger period of popularity than any\nother dog, having been in vogue for\nthirty years, and is still fairly popular,\"\nhe said.\nThe pug dog, and the old black and\ntun, or the terrier, which enjoyed an\nimmense popularity in the liO's and\nOil's are almost extinct and the dean\nsaid he knew of no one who still\nbreeds them. The chows, which were\nfavorites in 10110 are well liked.\nDean 1 Joskins lamented the passing\nof the collie, and regretted the current\nvogue for the police dog, saying lie\nwas not so gentle a companion as the\ncollie.\nHerman police dogs were brought\nback to America in great numbers\naboard army transports by officers\nand men of the army of occupation in\nGermany.\nNEGRO WOMEN TO APPEAL\nColored Females Protest Against Alleged\nDisfranchisement.\nNegro women of 2<> states, meeting\nin Washington at the call of the national\nassociation for the advancement\nof colored people today presented to\nthe National Woman's Party a request\nthat It urge congress to investigate\nthe alleged disfranchisement of negro\nwomen in tho south at the last general\nelection.\n\"Violations of the intent and purposes\nof the Susan B. Anthony amendment.\na statement prepared by the\nnegro women declared \"occurred in\nthe elections of 1020 in the southern\nstates and it has not been mad-1 secret\nthat wherever white women were\nnot allowed the ballot, it was counted\nworth while to relinguish it in order\nthat it might be denied colored women.\"\nDETECTIVE DRUMMOND\nWas Investigator of Original Ku Klux\nKlan.\nTlio death of A ml tow L. Dnimmonil.\n7(1. former chief of the United Slates\nsecret service, noted for his investigation\nof the original Ku Klux Klan\nwas announced in New York Monday.\nMe died at his home in Brooklyn Saturday.\nlie joined the secret service in 1S70\nand one of his lirst assignments was\nin connection with the famous Southern\nsecret organization, lie was made\nCiuej,' of the service in lS'Jl and retired\na few years oyo.\nNa t i o iial I xnt I oh- ?i C coat,, fuel, oil arid'\nwater power lands has been advoca-Hrd\nI by the secretary of the navy.\nmated at about $-5,000.\n\nE2 YEARS A POSTMASTER.\nNorth Carolina Man Has a Long Rec^\nv ord for Service.\nFifty-two yrat'S Of.eonUouous service\nas |iosimaster at South.; Creek.Ti'ea'fffort\ncounty, N. O., without a marl; ajyahist\nCongressional Delegate From Alaska to\ni Collect About 25,000.\nI Most full-fledged members of congress\nstruggle a Ion g on a salary of\nI about JO a day, says a Washington\ndispatch. James Wiekersham has been\nso favored that he probably will net\nabout $1,1)00 a day for being a territo|rial\ndelegate from Alaska, which means\nthat he cannot vote, hut only sit in the I\nhouse.\nHere is the reason:\nIn an election several years ago,\nWiekersham was declared defeated, lie\ntiled a contest and a congressional committee,\nfound that he was entitled to the\nscat. The investigation required a long\ntime and it was nut until the closing\ndays of that congress that the house\ndeclared him a. member. lie occupied\nhis seat for only a short time, hut was\nentitled to two years' salary, mileage i\nand other compensation, which is esti- j\nof high frequency X-rays in alleviating\ncancci*, but these particular rays\nhave not been used in America up to\nthis time.\n\"A vast amount of work has recently\nbeen done by Professor Dunne in\nthe detailed study of X-ray specter.\nSome of this work may prove effective\nin increasing the medical value of Xrays,\nbut much of it is being done\nsimply with the scientific purpose of\ngetting* to know more about the mysterious\nrays and the laws which govern\nthem.\n\"hong continued exposure to Xra.vs\nis so dangerous to the operator\nthat the greatest pains have to be\ntaken to protect' him from them. Tn\nthe Jefferson physical laboratory at\nHarvard, where Professor Dunne\nmakes his experiments, the X-ray\nplant is kept in a room by itself and\nthe rays are sent out through a minute\nslitslit in the wall. The brick wall at\nthis point is reinforced with lead and\na lead screen is placed across the\ndoor. Many experimenters in various\nplaces have been killed or seriously injured\nby constant use of X-rays, although\nthe exposure is so brief in the\ncase of patients I hat there is no danger\nto them. In the new building of\nthe cancer commission, the X-ray\nplant will have a roam to itself and\nthe rays will ha cent out through slits\nto do their benellcent work.\"\nVA/11 I ft PT RAf.k PAY.\nphysicists has been to secure this\nneeded quality.\n\"It was known that to secure penetration\nIt was necessarv to secure a\ni?. I J i\nhigh frequency of vibration. The\nHarvard physicists after a great number\nof experiments at length found\nthai a physical law known as the\n'quantum law' applied to the X-ray\nspectrum and discovered that they\ncould increase, the frequency of the\nrays, and thus their penetration, by\nincreasing the Voltage of current used\nin the X-my tube. Professor Duane\nreports that the tube goes to pieces\nunder a voltage of more than 150.000\nvolts, but that d sufficiently high voltage\nlias been soeured to make the Xrays\nvery nearly as effective for certain\nmedical purposes as the Gamma\nrays of radium.\n\"The Germans,'it is said, have made\ngreat headway recently with the use\nradium plant..\nConfident that the life of cancer patients\nmay thus he prolonged, life insurance\ncompanies of Boston have given\nover $30,000 toward the new building.\nv\nThe significance of the discovery\nwas explained in the following statement\nmade for tlie Associated Press\nat Harvard last Monday:\nV'The advantage of X-rays over radium\nis that the latter is scarce and\nimmensely expensive, costing at present\nover $100,000 a gram, and can\ntherefore only be used in small quantities.\nIf X-rays were used it would\nhe possible to make the rays enormously\nmore powerful than has been\npossible with the limited amount of\nradium available. The trouble with\nthe use of X-rays up to this time has\nbeen that they are not as penetrating\nas the so-called 'Gamma rays' of radium\nand the problem of the Harvard\nX-RAY FOR CANCER\nNew Discovery Promises Further\nProgress.\nRADIUM IS TOO SCARCE FOR USE\nPossible to Cure All Cases of the\nDreadful Disease,,, Scientists Are\nSatisfied That They Are Getting\nCloser to the Problem.\nDiscoveries made by William Dunne.\nprofessor of bio-physics at Harvard,\nworking in collaboration with research\nstucte of physics, have made it possible,\naccording to Harvard physicists,\nto secure X-rays of more penetrating\nquality-than have ever before been\nobtained in this country, and these\n<ie\\v rays are now to be used for the\nfirst time in America Cor the alleviation\nof cancer.\nWhile it is emphatically stated \"by\nProfessor Duanc that neither X-rays\nnor radium should be considered a permanent\ncure for all kinds of cancer, it\nhas long been known that radium lias\na marked alleviative effect upon this\ndisease, and the Harvard physicists\nhave reason to believe that the effect\nof the new highly penetrating X-rays\nwill be equally beneficial.The\nHarvard cancer commission is\nerecting a new building adjoining the\nCollis P. Huntington hospital in TtostonT\nwhere an X-ray plant will be installed,\nas well as the commission's\nhim. is the record of E. D. Springer.\nHis record is exceeded by one other\npostmaster in the United States, R. J.\nKnorr, of Clausville, Lehigh county,\nPennsylvania, who was appointed November\n13, 13G5.\nPostmaster Springer was born in\nMarch, 1838, at Cape May, New Jersey,\nand was a seafaring man in his early\nlife, serving in the United States navy\nduring the war between the states. He\ncame to ivorin \"jaronna in moo unu i\nwas appointed postmaster at South I\nCreek under President Grant's admin- I\nistmtion in 18G9.\nAlthough four score and three years.\nCaptain Springer continues to handle\npersonally the afftfTrs of the office at\nSouth Creek.\nWIFE FOOLED HUSBAND\nAdmits Five Children Were Not Her\nOwn.\nMm. Eva May Sv/ah., and officials\nof the Florida Children's Home Society\nrefused to deny or affirm the\ntruth of dispatches from Atlanta to\n(lie effect that Mrs. Swain had admitted\nto Georgia welfare officials\nthat slie had adopted live children and\nled her husband to believe that they\nwere her own, rcdateu :l Jacksonvi.le,\nFlorida c1. in patch.\nMrs. Swain's udmlnsion is said to\nhave followed statements made in At-\nlantri by her mother, Mrs. Alice South\nwho herself adopted 11 children i.ncludinr:\ntwo pairs of twins and triplets,\nthat she helped her daughter secure\nthe children. Mrs. Swain is said\nto hove made long- visits to her mother\nin Atlanta at the time of the \"birth\"\nof her children.\n\"Whatever she did, I believe she\ndid it with lite best intentions,\" said\nWil is Swain, of his wife today. Perhaps\nshe should not have concealed\nthe fact from me, but that will not\nmake any difference in pur relations.\nI love children an well as .site does and\nI guess we can tal.e care of the little\nones.\"\nSOUTH CAROLINA NEWS\nTom TI. Craig, a Adii'e man of\nAiKen county in unoer arrest at .-uiven\ncharged with the killing of Raymond\nBryant, also while of Aiken.\nThe Cash Cotton Mills of Greenville.\nwhich went into the hands of a\nreceiver several months ago, will be\nrc-organhsed.\nBam Tucker, ft negro man committed\nsuicide Wednesday l?.v stepping\nin front of a passing train at Woodruff.\nSpartanburg county.\nJohn G. Greer was on Tuesday\nelected a member of the house of representatives\nfront Greenville county to\nsucceed Tlios. P. Cothran, elevated to\nthe senate supreme court bench.\nThe annual meeting of thg TriStnie\nMedical Association whose membership\nembraces the C'arolinas find\nVirginm. was held in Spartanburg,\nthis week.\n?Adjutant General W. W. Moore n''\nSouth Carolina is in Washington I'm\nI he purpose of cheeking, if possible,\nthe plan of the war department to\ntransfer Infantry brigade beadf|iinrlei-s\nfrom South Carolina to North Carolina.\nSenator Crosson of Lexington\ncounty, proposes to introduce a hill\nin the senate to make the blowing of\nsafes in South Carolina where the\nblowing is committed fo>- larceny, a\ncrime punishable by death upon conviction.\nEdgelK-lri. February IS: Three burglars\nblew open the safe at the post office\nhere about 2.15 this morning and\ngot approximately $1,500 in stamps and\n$100 in cash. They escaped.'on foot,\nafter being shot at by the watchman\nand a policeman and returning the tire.\nAt a largely